ADD A TO B.
    GIVING C.
    DISPLAY C.
COMPUTE C = A + B.

SUBTRACT A FROM B.
COMPUTE C = A - B.

MULTIPLY A BY B.
COMPUTE C = A * B.

DIVIDE A INTO B.
COMPUTE C = A / B.

DIVIDE 10 INTO 100
    GIVING QUOTIENT
    REMAINDER LEFTOVER.
Can also "GIVING REMAINDER"

COBOL follows the order of operations, when multiple operations apply

Can use "ROUNDED", so "DIVIDE A INTO B ROUNDED." or "COMPUTE C ROUNDED = A / B."

REMINDER:
   DO MATH WITH 01 VALUE PIC 9(4)V99 (total of six integer placeholders).
       "V" is the implied decimal
       Can use "S" to designate positive/negative sign
   MOVE THE MATHEMATICAL NUMBER INTO 01 DISP-VALUE PIC ZZZ9.99
       Can use "$" to include monetary symbol
   DISPLAY DISP-VALUE.

ADD A TO B
    ON SIZE ERROR
        DISPLAY "[VALUE] TOO LARGE.".


REMINDER: Math should be computed by values of the same data "tier"
i.e.
01 GROSS-INVOICE.
   05 HOURS-WORKED ...
COMPUTE GROSS-INVOICE = HOURS-WORKED * HOURLY-RATE.
May result in overlapping memory usage, corrupted calculations, nonsensical results

COBOL does NOT inherently support trig functions, i.e., SIN, COS, TAN
But some compilers provide library functions like "CALL "SIN" USING ANGLE."  
Otherwise, precompute the value elsewhere.
Same with exlicit exponents or logarithms.

